{"parse":{"title":"headphone","pageid":573221,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"==English==\n{{wp}}\n[[File:Audio-Technica ATH-A500 (2).jpg|thumb|right|a pair of circumaural '''headphones''']]\n\n===Etymology===\n{{ety|en|:af|head|phone|text=+|tree=1}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈhɛdfəʊn/|a=RP}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-headphone.wav|a=Southern England}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈhɛdfoʊn/|a=US}}\n** {{audio|en|En-us-headphone.oga|a=GA}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈhedfəʉn/|a=AU}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈhedfɐʉn/|a=NZ}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈhɛdfon/|a=Scotland}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈhɛdfoːn/|a=Wales,non-toe-tow}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{lb|en|usually|in plural}} {{singular of|en|headphones}}: a cushioned speaker placed on, over, or inside the ear, normally used in left and right pairs.\n#: {{ux|en|Some joggers wear only one '''headphone''' in their ears, to enjoy music while paying attention to their environment.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2017| title=Electronica, Dance and Club Music|author=Mark J. Butler | page=| passage=From \"Little\" Louie Vega, David Camacho, and Tyrone Francis I learned about seamless beatmixing, using a so-called lollipop '''headphone''' for one ear and a monitor speaker for the other. }}\n# {{lb|en|attributive}} Used with [[headphones]].\n#: {{co|en|'''headphone''' plug}}\n#: {{co|en|'''headphone''' socket}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|en|headphone concert|headphoned|headphonelike}}\n\n====Related terms====\n{{col|en|earphone}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|listening device}}\n* Albanian: {{t+|sq|kufje|f}}\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|سَمَّاعَة|f}}, {{t|ar|سَمَاعَات رَأْس|f-p}} {{q|indefinite}}, {{t|ar|سَمَاعَات الرَّأْس|f-p}} {{q|definite}}, {{t|ar|أُرْصُوصَة|f}}, {{t|ar|أَرَاصِيص|p}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|ականջակալ}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{t|az|qulaqlıq}}\n* Belarusian: {{t|be|наву́шнікі|m-p}}\n* Bengali: {{t|bn|হেডফোন}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|слу́шалки|f-p}}\n* Burmese: {{t+|my|နားကြပ်}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|auricular|m}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{t|yue|耳機}}, {{t|yue|耳筒}}\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|耳機|tr=ěrjī}}, {{t|cmn|耳筒|tr=ěrtǒng}}\n*: Min Nan: {{t+|nan|耳機|tr=hīⁿ-ki}}\n* Czech: {{t|cs|sluchátka|n-p}}\n* Danish: {{t|da|hovedtelefon|c}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|hoofdtelefoon|m}}, {{t+|nl|koptelefoon|m}}\n* Esperanto: {{t+|eo|kapaŭskultilo}}\n* Estonian: {{t|et|kõrvaklapid|p}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kuulokkeet|p}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|écouteur|m}}, {{t+|fr|casque|m}}, {{t|fr|casque audio|m}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|ყურსაცვამი}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Kopfhörer|m}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|ακουστικό|n}}, {{t+|el|ακουστικά|n-p}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|אזנית|f|tr=oznít|alt=אָזְנִית / אוזניות}}\n* Hindi: {{t|hi|हेडफ़ोन|m}}, {{t|hi|हेड फ़ोन्स}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|fejhallgató}}\n* Icelandic: {{t+|is|heyrnartól|n}}\n* Indonesian: {{t|id|penyuara kuping}}, {{t|id|penyuara jemala}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|cluasán|m}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|auricolari|p}}, {{t+|it|cuffie|f-p}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|ヘッドフォン|tr=heddofon}}, {{t+|ja|ヘッドホン|tr=heddohon}}\n* Kazakh: {{t|kk|құлаққап}}, {{t|kk|тыңдауыр}}\n* Khmer: {{t+|km|កាស}}, {{t|km|កាសស្ដាប់ត្រចៀក}}\n* Korean: {{t|ko|헤드폰}}\n* Kyrgyz: {{t|ky|кулаккап}}, {{t|ky|кулакчын}}\n* Lao: {{t|lo|ຫູຟັງ}}\n* Latin: {{t|la|auscultābulum|n}}, {{t|la|concha auditoria|f}}\n* Latvian: {{t|lv|austiņas|f-p}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t|lt|ausinės|f-p}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|слушалки|f-p}}\n* Malay: {{t+|ms|fon kepala}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|pokitaringa}}\n* Mongolian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t+|mn|чихэвч}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t|nb|hodetelefon|m-p|alt=hodetelefoner}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{t|nn|hovudtelefon|m-p|alt=hovudtelefonar}}\n* Persian:\n*: Iranian Persian: {{t|fa-ira|هِدْفون|tr=hedfon}}, {{t+|fa-ira|دوگوشی|tr=doguši}}\n* Polish: {{t|pl|[[słuchawka|słuchawki]]|nv-p}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|fone de cabeça|m}}\n* Romanian: {{t|ro|căști|f-p}}, {{t|ro|căști audio|f-p}}, {{t|ro|căști auriculare|f-p}}, {{t+|ro|cască|f}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|нау́шники|m-p}}\n* Santali: {{t|sat|ᱦᱮᱰᱯᱷᱳᱱ}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|fòn-cluaise|m}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t|sh|слушалице|f